<subSubSection id="13935BB3FFDCF42DEA0D8BE6FEB07ECA" lastPageId="2" lastPageNumber="665" pageId="1" pageNumber="664" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="5B360838FFDCF42EEA0D8BE6FC557907" blockId="1.[811,1454,1201,1449]" pageId="1" pageNumber="664">
<emphasis id="69FDD42AFFDCF42EEA0D8BE6FC2478E7" bold="true" box="[811,928,1201,1225]" pageId="1" pageNumber="664">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="9C8973BBFFDCF42EEA808BE6FBD778E7" authorityName="Bührnheim &amp; Carvalho &amp; Malabarba &amp; Weitzman" authorityYear="2008" box="[934,1107,1201,1225]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Characidae" genus="Amazonspinther" kingdom="Animalia" order="Characiformes" pageId="1" pageNumber="664" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="69FDD42AFFDCF42EEA808BE6FBD778E7" box="[934,1107,1201,1225]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="664">Amazonspinther</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is diagnosed among all characid species by the autapomorphic presence of three conspicuous black blotches on the base of the dorsal, anal, and caudal fins (ch. 43; 
<figureCitation id="C3B214BDFFDCF42EEAA28A46FC467907" box="[900,962,1297,1321]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="1.[129,168,1932,1956]" captionTargetBox="[131,1454,1486,1912]" captionTargetId="figure-626@1.[131,1454,1486,1912]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="Fig. 1. Holotype of Amazonspinther dalmata, new species, MCP 38623, undetermined sex, 19.63 mm SL." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4567161" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4567161/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="664">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="5B360838FFDCF42DEA778A66FD5D7D8D" blockId="1.[811,1454,1201,1449]" lastBlockId="2.[134,777,172,740]" lastPageId="2" lastPageNumber="665" pageId="1" pageNumber="664">
<taxonomicName id="9C8973BBFFDCF42EEA778A66FB857967" authorityName="Bührnheim &amp; Carvalho &amp; Malabarba &amp; Weitzman" authorityYear="2008" box="[849,1025,1329,1353]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Characidae" genus="Amazonspinther" kingdom="Animalia" order="Characiformes" pageId="1" pageNumber="664" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="69FDD42AFFDCF42EEA778A66FB857967" box="[849,1025,1329,1353]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="664">Amazonspinther</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is diagnosed among all genera of the 
<taxonomicName id="9C8973BBFFDCF42EEA0D8A06FC4B7947" baseAuthorityName="Malabarba" baseAuthorityYear="1998" box="[811,975,1361,1385]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Characidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Characiformes" pageId="1" pageNumber="664" phylum="Chordata" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Cheirodontinae">Cheirodontinae</taxonomicName>
by two uniquely derived characters, the anteriormost proximal radial of the anal fin with an anteriorly extended lamina entering the abdominal cavity, between the distal portions of the 12th to 14th pleural ribs (ch. 44; 
<figureCitation id="C3B214BDFFDFF42DEBE48FFBFC847CEA" box="[706,768,172,196]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="2.[134,173,1247,1271]" captionTargetBox="[134,777,761,1232]" captionTargetId="figure-555@2.[134,777,761,1233]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Fig. 2. Lateral view (left side) of the anteriormost proximal radial of the anal fin of Amazonspinther dalmata, showing the anteriorly extended lamina entering the abdominal cavity (MCP 37572, 14.98 mm SL, c&amp;s)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4567163" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4567163/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="665">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
) (
<emphasis id="69FDD42AFFDFF42DE9A98F9BFF217CCD" box="[143,165,204,227]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="665">vs</emphasis>
. short anteriorly extended lamina, not entering the abdominal cavity and not between pleural ribs), and by the extremely elongate caudal peduncle, corresponding to 27.3-30.2% of SL. Caudal peduncle length is comparatively short in cheirodontines, ranging from 11.0 to 19.6% of SL. 
<taxonomicName id="9C8973BBFFDFF42DEB4F8E1BFE857DAA" authorityName="Eigenmann" authorityYear="1911" class="Actinopterygii" family="Characidae" genus="Spintherobolus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Characiformes" pageId="2" pageNumber="665" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="papilliferus">
<emphasis id="69FDD42AFFDFF42DEB4F8E1BFE857DAA" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="665">Spintherobolus papilliferus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has an elongate caudal peduncle (21.3-27.0% of SL), but shorter than that observed for 
<taxonomicName id="9C8973BBFFDFF42DEB038EDBFD567D8A" authorityName="Bührnheim &amp; Carvalho &amp; Malabarba &amp; Weitzman" authorityYear="2008" box="[549,722,396,420]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Characidae" genus="Amazonspinther" kingdom="Animalia" order="Characiformes" pageId="2" pageNumber="665" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="69FDD42AFFDFF42DEB038EDBFD567D8A" box="[549,722,396,420]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="665">Amazonspinther</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<caption id="0FF658B0FFDCF42EE9A788DBFB687B8A" ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4567161" ID-Zenodo-Dep="4567161" box="[129,1260,1932,1956]" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4567161/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="664" startId="1.[129,168,1932,1956]" targetBox="[131,1454,1486,1912]" targetPageId="1">
<paragraph id="5B360838FFDCF42EE9A788DBFB687B8A" blockId="1.[129,1260,1932,1956]" box="[129,1260,1932,1956]" pageId="1" pageNumber="664">
<emphasis id="69FDD42AFFDCF42EE9A788DBFF437B8A" bold="true" box="[129,199,1932,1956]" pageId="1" pageNumber="664">Fig. 1.</emphasis>
Holotype of 
<taxonomicName id="9C8973BBFFDCF42EE87288DBFDDB7B8A" authority="Bührnheim &amp; Carvalho &amp; Malabarba &amp; Weitzman, 2008" authorityName="Bührnheim &amp; Carvalho &amp; Malabarba &amp; Weitzman" authorityYear="2008" box="[340,607,1932,1956]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Characidae" genus="Amazonspinther" kingdom="Animalia" order="Characiformes" pageId="1" pageNumber="664" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="dalmata" status="new species">
<emphasis id="69FDD42AFFDCF42EE87288DBFDDB7B8A" box="[340,607,1932,1956]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="664">Amazonspinther dalmata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicNameLabel id="72CE6951FFDCF42EEB4B88DBFD747B8A" box="[621,752,1932,1956]" pageId="1" pageNumber="664" rank="species">new species</taxonomicNameLabel>
, MCP 38623, undetermined sex, 19.63 mm SL.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph id="5B360838FFDFF42DE98A8EFBFEB07ECA" blockId="2.[134,777,172,740]" pageId="2" pageNumber="665">
Among all genera of the tribe 
<taxonomicName id="9C8973BBFFDFF42DE8C68EFBFDF27DEA" box="[480,630,428,452]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Characidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Characiformes" pageId="2" pageNumber="665" phylum="Chordata" rank="tribe" tribe="Cheirodontini">Cheirodontini</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="9C8973BBFFDFF42DEB588EFBFF357DCA" authorityName="Bührnheim &amp; Carvalho &amp; Malabarba &amp; Weitzman" authorityYear="2008" class="Actinopterygii" family="Characidae" genus="Amazonspinther" kingdom="Animalia" order="Characiformes" pageId="2" pageNumber="665" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="69FDD42AFFDFF42DEB588EFBFF357DCA" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="665">Amazonspinther</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is diagnosed by two features: a small number of ventral procurrent caudal-fin rays (7-9 
<emphasis id="69FDD42AFFDFF42DE8FF8EBBFE727E2D" box="[473,502,492,515]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="665">vs.</emphasis>
11-28; Malabarba, 1998: 205-207, 209, ch. 42; Weitzman &amp; Malabarba, 1999:8-9, ch. 5; 
<quantity id="9C71A5DDFFDFF42DE9B98D7BFF727E6A" box="[159,246,556,580]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.429" metricValueMax="4.064" metricValueMin="2.794" pageId="2" pageNumber="665" unit="in" value="13.5" valueMax="16.0" valueMin="11.0">11-16 in</quantity>
<taxonomicName id="9C8973BBFFDFF42DE9DD8D7BFE1F7E6A" authorityName="Eigenmann" authorityYear="1911" box="[251,411,556,580]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Characidae" genus="Spintherobolus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Characiformes" pageId="2" pageNumber="665" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="69FDD42AFFDFF42DE9DD8D7BFE1F7E6A" box="[251,411,556,580]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="665">Spintherobolus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species) (
<figureCitation id="C3B214BDFFDFF42DEB248D7BFDC57E6A" box="[514,577,556,580]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="2.[134,173,1870,1894]" captionTargetBox="[134,792,1382,1850]" captionTargetId="figure-556@2.[136,779,1390,1854]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Fig. 3. Posterior caudal vertebrae and associated bone elements of Amazonspinther dalmata (left side view) (MCP 37572, 14.98 mm SL, c&amp;s)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4567165" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4567165/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="665">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
); and hemal spines of one, two, or sometimes three posterior caudal vertebrae directly articulating with the ventral procurrent caudal-fin rays (
<figureCitation id="C3B214BDFFDFF42DE9A88DDBFF4B7E8A" box="[142,207,652,676]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="2.[134,173,1870,1894]" captionTargetBox="[134,792,1382,1850]" captionTargetId="figure-556@2.[136,779,1390,1854]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Fig. 3. Posterior caudal vertebrae and associated bone elements of Amazonspinther dalmata (left side view) (MCP 37572, 14.98 mm SL, c&amp;s)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4567165" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4567165/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="665">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
; 
<emphasis id="69FDD42AFFDFF42DE9FA8DDBFF767E8D" box="[220,242,652,675]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="665">vs</emphasis>
. hemal spines of at least the four posterior caudal vertebrae directly articulating with the ventral procurrent caudal-fin rays).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="13935BB3FFDFF42DEA168FFCFAE27D6D" pageId="2" pageNumber="665" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="5B360838FFDFF42DEA168FFCFAE27D6D" blockId="2.[816,1460,171,323]" pageId="2" pageNumber="665">
<emphasis id="69FDD42AFFDFF42DEA168FFCFC327CED" bold="true" box="[816,950,171,195]" pageId="2" pageNumber="665">Etymology.</emphasis>
<emphasis id="69FDD42AFFDFF42DEAE68FFCFB9D7CEC" box="[960,1049,171,194]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="665">Amazon</emphasis>
, in reference to the Amazon basin, and 
<emphasis id="69FDD42AFFDFF42DEA468F9CFC337CCD" box="[864,951,203,227]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="665">spinther</emphasis>
from the Greek 
<emphasis id="69FDD42AFFDFF42DED558F9CFB4E7CCD" box="[1139,1226,203,227]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="665">spinther</emphasis>
, masculine, meaning sparks, fire, in reference to both the closely related genus 
<taxonomicName id="9C8973BBFFDFF42DEA168E5CFC487D0D" authorityName="Eigenmann" authorityYear="1911" box="[816,972,267,291]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Characidae" genus="Spintherobolus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Characiformes" pageId="2" pageNumber="665" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="69FDD42AFFDFF42DEA168E5CFC487D0D" box="[816,972,267,291]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="665">Spintherobolus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and to the appearance of the yellow neuromasts of the head, also observed in 
<taxonomicName id="9C8973BBFFDFF42DED4E8E7CFA8D7D6D" authorityName="Eigenmann" authorityYear="1911" box="[1128,1289,299,323]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Characidae" genus="Spintherobolus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Characiformes" pageId="2" pageNumber="665" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="69FDD42AFFDFF42DED4E8E7CFA8D7D6D" box="[1128,1289,299,323]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="665">Spintherobolus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation id="C3B214BDFFDFF42DEC318E7CFADD7D6D" box="[1303,1369,299,323]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="2.[816,855,1869,1893]" captionTargetBox="[813,1459,1374,1859]" captionTargetId="figure-614@2.[816,1459,1382,1859]" captionText="Fig. 4. Lateral view (left side) of the head of the holotype of Amazonspinther dalmata showing the pattern of neuromasts distribution (MCP 38623, 19.63 mm SL)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5070429" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5070429/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="665">Fig. 4</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
